AB  - In this paper, a novel multi-time Local Outlier Factor (MT-LOF) algorithm is proposed to address the challenges posed by the low efficiency of automated imaging of ultrasound data and the difficulty of reusing the results. MT-LOF is employed to summarize ultrasound outlier signals at multiple time points and reconstruct detection results. Additionally, phased array ultrasonic testing (PAUT) boards are utilized to collect data from flat-bottomed holes, simulated impact components, and real specimens. The collected data is then processed using the MT-LOF and gate peak method, and the results are compared. The findings of the research suggest that MT-LOF can effectively streamline the ultrasonic signal processing process, achieve automated characterization of ultrasonic defect data, and concurrently enhance the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of the impact simulation sample experiment by 176.7% in comparison with conventional methods, while concomitantly reducing the background standard deviation by 44.7%.
