TI  - Ultrasonic signal processing and AI for detecting defects caused by excess sand in concrete structures
T2  - CASE STUDIES IN CONSTRUCTION MATERIALS
LA  - English
KW  - Concrete defects
KW  - Nondestructive testing
KW  - Signal processing
KW  - Correlation analysis
KW  - Frequency analysis
KW  - Wavelet decomposition
KW  - Artificial neural network
KW  - STRENGTH
AB  - While concrete mix design has been widely investigated, the specific influence of excess sand on ultrasonic signal propagation and its reliable detection remains insufficiently explored, despite its critical impact on durability and structural safety. Excess sand can weaken mechanical strength, reduce durability, and impair the bond with reinforcement, thereby increasing the risk of structural deficiencies. Detecting such defects in hardened concrete is essential for safety and maintenance, yet remains challenging due to the material's heterogeneous nature. This study introduces a novel approach combining ultrasonic testing with AI-based analysis to address this issue. A controlled laboratory case study was carried out using standard cylindrical specimens (160 mm x 320 mm, cement content of 350 kg/m3), where defective mixes were prepared by systematically increasing sand content from 5 % to 30 % in 5 % increments while keeping cement, gravel, and water constant. Ultrasonic testing was performed with "Pundit PL 200" transducers, and advanced signal processing techniques-including correlation analysis, frequency content evaluation, signal energy computation, and wavelet decomposition-were applied. The extracted features were used to train a feedforward artificial neural network (ANN), which achieved an accuracy of 96.97 %, an F1-score of 0.97, and a mean squared error below 0.005. These findings validate the effectiveness of the proposed methodology for reliable and non-destructive evaluation of concrete structures such as bridges, tunnels, dams, and buildings.
