TI  - Research on ultrasonic non-destructive detection method for defects in GFRP laminates based on machine learning
T2  - OCEAN ENGINEERING
LA  - English
KW  - Machine learning
KW  - GFRP laminates
KW  - Ultrasonic testing
KW  - Non-destructive detection
KW  - 3D-ResNet50-CBAM model
AB  - As the main load-bearing structure of yachts, glass fiber reinforced plastic (GFRP) laminates are susceptible to internal delamination and blistered defects due to the manufacturing process and material characteristics, which seriously threaten the structural strength and safety of yachts. The traditional ultrasonic testing (UT) method relies on manual experience, making it inefficient and prone to a high false detection rate. To improve the efficiency and accuracy of non-destructive testing, this paper proposes a method for defect detection in GFRP laminates based on ultrasonic B-scan images. Through the hand-layup process and array ultrasonic testing technology, a B-scan ultrasonic dataset of GFRP laminates was constructed, including non-defective samples and samples with delamination and blistered defects of varying locations and sizes. Wavelet packet decomposition extracted features from the data. In response to energy differences of defects in certain wavelet packet subbands, a random forest (RF) method was employed to select relevant subbands, avoiding interference from redundant features. In the classification stage, combining the 3D residual network (3D-ResNet50) model and the channel and spatial attention module (CBAM) significantly improved spatio-temporal feature extraction, focusing on key ones. The final classification accuracy reached 99.00 %. This approach enhanced both efficiency and accuracy of GFRP sheet defect detection.
