AB  - The coupling of multimodal ultrasonic waves generated by pulsed lasers, combined with wave scattering caused by surface roughness and randomly distributed pores, presents significant challenges for achieving high-resolution defect imaging in metal additive manufacturing (MAM) components using conventional ultrasonic methods. This article proposes a probabilistic imaging strategy based on a hybrid deep learning algorithm, namely a graph neural network integrated with a one-class support vector machine (GNN-OCSVM), for subsurface defect characterization using laser ultrasonics. The graph neural network (GNN)-based denoising module enhances the signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) by aggregating correlated features through topological relationships among ultrasonic signals. Subsequently, the one-class support vector machine (OCSVM) algorithm estimates the probability of defect presence from the denoised signals, enabling probabilistic reconstruction of C-scan images of subsurface defects. Laser ultrasonic experiments were conducted on AlSi10Mg and TC4 MAM specimens containing subsurface defects of varying sizes and geometries. The experimental results demonstrate that the GNN-OCSVM algorithm: 1) achieves superior defect boundary definition compared to scanning acoustic microscopy (SAM); 2) maintains a relative dimensional error of merely 2%-6% when benchmarked against X-ray imaging; and 3) outperforms other anomaly detection algorithms (ADAs), including Deep Isolation Forest, K-Means and TimesNet, in both defect shape reconstruction accuracy and size measurement precision. These findings demonstrate that the proposed AI algorithm, combined with laser ultrasonics, provides enhanced imaging accuracy for subsurface defect detection under challenging multimodal wave coupling conditions, offering a viable solution for nondestructive evaluation of additive-manufactured components.
