TI  - Advancing one-sided nondestructive testing for denoising: integrating deep learning for enhanced defect detection and quality assurance
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF ADVANCED MANUFACTURING TECHNOLOGY
LA  - English
KW  - Nondestructive testing
KW  - One-sided inspection
KW  - Deep learning
KW  - Defect detection
KW  - Quality assurance
KW  - Ultrasonic testing
KW  - NDT
AB  - This paper presents a comprehensive study on the enhancement of one-sided nondestructive testing (NDT) methods-ultrasonic testing (UT), eddy current testing (ECT), and radiographic testing (RT)-through the application of AI models. The primary focus is on improving defect detection accuracy, signal-to-noise ratio (SNR), and reducing the minimum detectable defect size. For UT, a convolutional neural network (CNN) was employed to process deconvolved ultrasonic signals, achieving a defect size detection of 0.8 mm and improving SNR to 35 dB with an accuracy rate of 98%. ECT was enhanced using a recurrent neural network (RNN) with long short-term memory (LSTM) layers, reducing the defect size detection to 0.3 mm, increasing SNR to 45 dB, and achieving a detection accuracy of 99%. In RT, a deep convolutional generative adversarial network (DCGAN) was used to enhance X-ray image quality, enabling the detection of defects as small as 0.7 mm with an SNR of 40 dB and a detection probability of 97%. Although CNN, RNN, and DCGAN are applied independently to different NDT modalities (UT, ECT, RT, respectively), their selection is strategically aligned for hybrid system integration. Each model complements the others by targeting distinct signal characteristics-spatial, temporal, and generative-within a unified deep learning-driven NDT framework. Compared to traditional NDT methods, the proposed deep learning-enhanced framework demonstrates significant improvements, including up to 20% higher accuracy and 15-25% SNR gain, based on identical input signals. These results highlight the potential of neural architectures to significantly improve the efficiency, accuracy, and reliability of NDT processes. Despite these advancements, challenges such as the need for extensive datasets and high computational power remain, signaling areas for future research.
