AB  - Additively manufactured (AM) lattice structures enable unprecedented strength-to-weight optimization and multifunctional performance across aerospace, biomedical, defence, and energy applications. However, their architected geometries characterized by thin struts, nodal overlap, periodic topology, and open porosity introduce defect-detectability challenges that fundamentally differ from those in monolithic AM components. Process induced imperfections such as porosity, lack of fusion, geometric distortion, and micro cracking can significantly compromise mechanical reliability, fatigue resistance, and structural integrity, necessitating geometry-aware non-destructive evaluation (NDE) strategies. This review presents a comprehensive, lattice-centric analysis of NDE techniques applied to metal and polymer lattice architectures, including X-ray computed tomography, ultrasonic testing, acoustic emission, infrared thermography, eddy-current testing, magnetic methods, and resonant acoustic approaches. For each modality, defect sensitivity, lattice-specific limitations, and applicability across AM processes are critically examined. Comparative and defect-oriented decision frameworks are introduced to guide method selection based on defect scale, penetration depth, topology sensitivity, throughput, and cost constraints. The review further synthesizes the convergence of machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) within lattice-centric NDE workflows. Distinct learning paradigms supervised, unsupervised, selfsupervised, physics-informed, transfer-learning, and uncertainty-aware frameworks are systematically differentiated with respect to ground-truth strategies, interpretability, generalization, and certification readiness. ML is positioned as a modality-agnostic interpretive layer enabling segmentation refinement, multimodal fusion, probability-of-detection analysis, and performance-correlated digital qualification. Finally, emerging directions in physics-informed ML, multimodal sensor fusion, uncertainty quantification, digital twin integration, and ISO/ ASTM-aligned standardization are discussed. The review establishes that the future of AM lattice inspection lies in integrated, AI-augmented, and performance-driven NDE ecosystems that are inherently lattice-aware and industrially scalable.
