AB  - Debonding in concrete-filled steel tube (CFST) arch bridges can significantly reduce their bearing capacity and service life. Traditional methods for detecting this debonding largely depend on the subjective judgment of inspectors, which can be unreliable. This paper introduces a nondestructive testing method utilizing ultrasonic waves to monitor debonding defects in CFST. Nine steel tube concretes with varying debonding defects were monitored using the radial-pair measurement method. To classify these defects, we developed a defect recognition model called BO-LSTM, which combines Bayesian optimization (BO) with long short-term memory (LSTM) networks, based on the traditional ultrasonic testing principles for CFST. This algorithm addresses the inherent parameter tuning challenges of traditional methods and can effectively capture the characteristic information of ultrasonic defects in CFST. The BO-LSTM model is compared with three conventional classification algorithms including random forest (RF), gradient boosting decision tree (GBDT) and extreme gradient boosting (XGBoost). Experimental results demonstrate that the BO-LSTM model achieves optimal performance with prediction accuracies of 100%, 99.3%, and 99.3% for CFST specimens of three degrees of debonding, respectively. To enhance model interpretability, SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) analysis was employed to quantify the contribution of each input feature, providing transparent insights into the model's decision-making process. Consequently, this method holds promise for enhancing the application of ultrasonic inspection technology in the real-world evaluation of arch bridges, thereby improving the quality of arch bridge construction.
