AB  - Although polymer concrete (PC), a thermally sensitive material composed of epoxy resin and aggregates, requires robust health monitoring under thermal exposure, limited studies have utilized novel non-destructive tests and analyzing methods to achieve this task. This study employed the ultrasonic test (UT) and artificial intelligence to assess damages in PC specimens with varying epoxy resin content subjected to different temperatures. Self-organizing map defined specimens' damage stages using 1800 sinusoidal ultrasonic signals (SUSs) obtained from UT. Damage stages were predicted using: (1) a long short-term memory processing raw SUSs, (2) 2D matrices generated by wavelet transform of SUSs analyzed through a convolutional neural network, and (3) a multi-layer perceptron classifying gray-level co-occurrence matrix (GLCM) features from 2D matrices. A regression model predicted PC's relative absorbed thermal energy. Transfer learning pre-trained all models, and Monte Carlo sampling defined damage stages' probabilities. The specimens' compressive strength was determined to validate UT's results. Minimum compressive strength loss of 53 MPa from 250 degrees C to 300 degrees C indicates PC's rapid damage progression. Specimens with lower epoxy resin content exhibit superior thermal behavior than those with higher content at temperatures above 250 degrees C. The third and first approaches depict the best and worst performances with 100 % and 82 % training accuracy, respectively. Generating 2D matrices from the wavelet transform of SUSs and utilizing their GLCM features is highly effective and can be a robust feature-extraction method for SUSs in future studies.
