AB  - Defects arising during lithium-ion battery manufacturing are a critical factor triggering thermal runaway. Accurately detecting and differentiating various battery defects is vital for enhancing battery safety. Conventional electrochemical-based production quality control has limitations since electrochemical tests cannot capture all potential failure precursors and offer detailed internal structural information. To tackle this challenge, we propose an intelligent defect-detection algorithm based on focused ultrasonic transmission technology. We fabricated battery samples with various manufacturing defects and conducted ultrasonic testing and analysis. The results show that mainstream waveform features like acoustic energy, time of flight, maximum amplitude, and waveform coefficient are insufficient for accurately classifying defects on battery electrodes. Subsequently, we employed feature-evaluation algorithms to extract critical features from ultrasound waveforms and combined machine-learning techniques to classify internal battery defects. The algorithm accurately identified various defects on battery anodes and cathodes, including lithium deposition, material shedding, separator wrinkles, contaminants, gas, and poor wetting, with a defect - classification accuracy of 99.95 % and high robustness. This method is compatible with existing ultrasound-testing equipment and can be integrated into production lines. It shows great potential for efficient and precise detection in large-scale automated production and is expected to enhance overall battery safety and resource utilization.
