AB  - In powder-polymer composite processing, determining Critical Solids Loading (CSL) is crucial for identifying the maximum powder loading at which a continuous polymer phase can still wet and disperse all particles before particle-particle contacts dominate and powder-binder separation and void formation occur, leading to parts with defects and reduced mechanical properties. CSL thus marks a transition from polymer-controlled viscous flow to contact-mechanical interactions governed by inter-particle friction and packing. Traditional CSL estimation relies on manual interpretation of torque mixing curves, which introduces subjectivity and reproducibility challenges. This study interprets CSL through this physical transition framework and uses an unsupervised machine learning technique, K-means clustering, to objectively locate the transition point by iteratively clustering torque mixing data for PBT-alumina composites with spherical and non-spherical alumina morphologies. The integrated approach identifies CSL values of 52 vol% for spherical alumina and 48 vol% for non-spherical alumina, with the earlier transition in non-spherical systems reflecting a more rapid loss of polymer phase continuity and the onset of particle-dominated contact networks. Beyond CSL, torque values diverge sharply between morphologies: non-spherical alumina exhibits erratic fluctuations, whereas spherical alumina shows a more gradual, near-linear increase, as confirmed through linear fitting of the clustered regions. A complementary CSL estimation method based on energy dissipation-quantified by totalized torque at incremental powder loadings-corroborates these findings. Microstructural validation using SEM and density measurements reveals distinct polymer-particle interactions at the identified CSL points and highlights different powder-binder separation mechanisms beyond CSL, illustrating the strong influence of particle morphology on composite flow behavior.
